<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-414-325  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 414 325.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  July 3 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Japan: most viruses hit Macintosh computers.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Takahashi, Ken.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Product:   Apple Macintosh (Microcomputer) (computer programs).andO;Topic:     Computer virusesJapanReports.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>JAPAN: MOST VIRUSES HIT MACINTOSH COMPUTERS TOKYO, JAPAN, 1990 JUN 22 (NB) --The Apple Macintosh is the computer most susceptible to virus attacks inJapan, according to research conducted by IPA or Information-technologyPromotion Agency, the affiliate of Japan's Ministry of International Tradeand Industry.andM;When IPA conducted a survey of 500 facilities, such as universities, publicresearch institutes, and manufacturers this March, 51 facilities reported 55cases in which their computers had been damaged by computer viruses: 46 casesfor Macintosh, 2 for NEC PC-9801, one for a VAX minicomputer of DEC, one fora Sun workstation of Sun Microsystems, and five for other computers.andM;Among the viruses affecting Macintosh computers, there were 29 VIR viruseswhich destroyed stored files and 3 WDEF viruses which damaged stored files.andO;Both types of viruses are believed to have originated in the U.S.andP;  andEurope.andM;IPA highly recommends that people avoid use of copied programs, downloadedprograms from online networks, and floppy disk rentals, in order to preventvirus infections.andM;(Ken Takahashi/19900628)</TEXT></DOC>